latestPosts.caption:
Oh, my darling boy. People who hated cats always held Bagheera as an exception. Sure, I love cats that are aloof and independent, but he was the antithesis of both of those things. He was starving and parasite-ridden when I found him, and he still purred when I picked him up. From the second I saw him until the moment I said goodbye, there was no moment where he didn’t want to be held and touched.

I’ve had pets my whole life, and while I recognized that he was special in this way (most of my cats would make it clear that I had about two seconds to put them down before it was going to be a fight), at first I loved him the way I’d loved all my others. Which is a LOT of love, but it wasn’t the obsessive, bonded love it turned into. It wasn’t until one summer in NH when an accident made him lose part of his tail that we got closer. He was running around, bleeding, confused, and in pain. It was like he knew the pain was coming from behind him, so if he could just run fast enough, he’d get away from whatever was hurting him. I felt terrible for him and wanted to catch him so I could take him to the vet. But all my attempts were in vain.

Finally, feeling defeated, I sat on the floor crosslegged. He stopped running and walked over to me, crawling into my lap and starting to purr. No, it wasn’t a happy purr, it wasn’t an affectionate purr, it was a self-soothing purr, but I realized in that moment that he associated ME with safety. That his trust in me was immense and even though he couldn’t reason through it the way a human could, he knew “she will be able to make this better.”

After that, I was just as fully his as he was mine. Sometimes people would tell us we had an abnormal bond. Even at the vet as he got older and needed technician-only appointments to administer arthritis shots and check his vitals, they had a note in his file that I had to come in with him. It wasn’t something I requested, and it wasn’t because he was aggressive. It was because they could never get an accurate reading of his blood pressure without me there because he was so stressed out, and my presence quantifiably soothed him. (Continued in comments)
